  <p>These indicators are publicly available. They do not require insider information. Any investor, business operator, or diaspora founder can track them through Bank of Ghana publications, Ministry of Finance budget reports, and the Ghana Statistical Service quarterly releases.</p>

  <h2 id="fiscal-council">The Independent Fiscal Council</h2>

  <p>The single most important institutional development in this IMF cycle is the announcement of an Independent Fiscal Council. If implemented with genuine independence, legal authority, and operational funding, this institution could break the historical pattern.</p>

  <p>The theory is sound: an independent body that publicly scores government fiscal plans, flags deviations, and issues binding or semi-binding recommendations creates a domestic substitute for IMF conditionality. Countries with effective fiscal councils (Chile, Sweden, the United Kingdom) have better fiscal outcomes than those without.</p>

  <div class="risk-box">
    <h4>Honest Assessment: Fiscal Council Risk</h4>
    <p>Ghana has announced institutional reforms before that were never fully implemented or were implemented without genuine independence. The key questions are:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Will the Fiscal Council have its own budget line, or will it depend on Finance Ministry allocations?</li>
      <li>Will its members be appointed through a transparent, non-partisan process?</li>
      <li>Will its recommendations be legally binding, or advisory only?</li>
      <li>Will it have access to real-time fiscal data, or will it receive delayed reports?</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Confidence: LOW.</strong> The council has been announced but not yet established. Until legislation is passed and the council is operational, this remains a promise, not a safeguard.</p>
  </div>

  <p>Tracking the Fiscal Council's progress from announcement to legislation to operation to first independent report will be one of the most important governance indicators of 2026 and 2027.</p>

  <h2 id="eurobond-restructuring">Eurobond Restructuring: The Unfinished Business</h2>

  <p>Ghana's debt restructuring has two components. The domestic component (DDEP) is complete. The international component (Eurobond restructuring) is in late-stage negotiations but not yet finalised as of March 2026.</p>

  <p>This matters because incomplete Eurobond restructuring means Ghana's external debt burden is not fully resolved. If the restructuring concludes on favourable terms, Ghana's debt-to-GDP trajectory improves further, reinforcing the stability window. If negotiations stall or produce less favourable terms than expected, the debt sustainability picture weakens.</p>

  <p>Eurobond restructuring also affects Ghana's ability to return to international capital markets. A clean restructuring with high creditor participation reopens market access. A contentious restructuring with holdout creditors could delay market access and increase future borrowing costs.</p>

  <div class="risk-box">
    <h4>Eurobond Status</h4>
    <p><strong>Current status:</strong> Late-stage negotiations. Terms not yet public.</p>
    <p><strong>Risk:</strong> Delay or unfavourable terms could undermine the post-IMF fiscal position.</p>
    <p><strong>Confidence: MEDIUM.</strong> Progress has been steady, but final terms are uncertain.</p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="scenario-analysis">Scenario Analysis</h2>

  <p>Three scenarios for Ghana's first 18 months post-IMF exit (August 2026 to February 2028):</p>

  <p><strong>Discipline Holds (40% probability).</strong> The Fiscal Council is established with genuine independence. Supplementary budgets remain within 2% of the original. The fiscal deficit stays below 3% of GDP. The BoG maintains its inflation-targeting credibility. The cedi remains stable. In this scenario, the stability window extends beyond mid-2027, potentially to early 2028. Business conditions remain favourable. Ghana breaks the historical pattern for the first time.</p>

  <p><strong>Gradual Drift (40% probability).</strong> The base case informed by historical pattern. Fiscal discipline holds through Q1 2027. By mid-2027, supplementary budgets expand spending by 3 to 5% above the original budget. The Fiscal Council is established but lacks enforcement power or operational independence. Inflation creeps above 8% by late 2027. The cedi depreciates 10 to 15% from current levels. Business conditions remain workable but deteriorating. This is the scenario that requires a defined exit or hedge strategy.</p>

  <p><strong>Accelerated Erosion (20% probability).</strong> A commodity price shock (cocoa collapse, oil spike) combines with premature fiscal loosening. Revenue shortfalls are met with domestic borrowing rather than spending cuts. The Fiscal Council is sidelined or not yet operational. Inflation returns above 15% within 18 months of IMF exit. The cedi enters a depreciation cycle. Business conditions deteriorate rapidly. This scenario is the familiar pattern, accelerated by external shocks.</p>

